  "text": "The most important rule to notice is ! r : as Cntr is performed only on !-discharged variables, during reduction only ! typed terms will be duplicated; the ! r rule ensures that duplicable terms have at most one occurrence of free variable. This is one of the keys that ensure the polynomial bound for the reduction of these terms ( [CITATION_1] ). Another important point is a stratification property ensured by the ! and § connectives: in particular note that to ! discharge a variable x (thus making it contractible) one has to apply a ! r or a § r rules and add an exponential to the type of the term.",
